simulate two datasets

set.seed(1)

n_samp = 250

sim_df_const = 
  tibble(x = rnorm(n_samp, 1, 1),
         error = rnorm(n_samp, 0, 1),
         y = 2 + 3*x + error
         )

sim_df_nonconst = 
  sim_df_const |> 
  mutate(
    error = .75 * error * x,
    y = 2 + 3*x + error
  )

look at these data

sim_df_const |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point()

sim_df_nonconst |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point()

Write a function to draw a bootstrap sample.

boot_sample = function(df) {
  sample_frac(df, size = 1, replace = TRUE)
}

^replace = TRUE tells us to get a different sample everytime

does this work?

sim_df_nonconst |> 
  boot_sample() |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .5) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  xlim(c(-2,4)) +
  ylim(c(-5,16))
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

formalize this a bit and extract results. we generate our bootstrap samples here

boot_straps = 
  tibble(
    iter = 1:5000
  ) |> 
  mutate(
    bootstrap_sample = map(iter, \(i) boot_sample(df = sim_df_nonconst))
  )

\(i) uses this (i) instead of iter???

(quick check)

boot_straps |> 
  pull(bootstrap_sample) |> 
  nth(2) |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = x, y = y)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .5) +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm", se = FALSE) +
  xlim(c(-2,4)) +
  ylim(c(-5,16))
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

actually run my analyses!!

bootstrap_results = 
  boot_straps |> 
  mutate(
    fits = map(bootstrap_sample, \(df) lm(y ~ x, data = df)),
    results = map(fits, broom::tidy)
  )

look at results

bootstrap_results |> 
  select(iter, results) |> 
  unnest(results) |> 
  group_by(term) |> 
  summarize(
    mean = mean(estimate),
    se = sd(estimate)
  )
## # A tibble: 2  3
##   term         mean     se
##   <chr>       <dbl>  <dbl>
## 1 (Intercept)  1.93 0.0762
## 2 x            3.11 0.103

do it again but faster this time

bootstrap_results = 
  sim_df_nonconst |> 
  bootstrap(n = 5000) |> 
  mutate(
    df = map(strap, as_tibble),
    fits = map(df, \(df) lm(y ~ x, data = df)),
    results = map(fits, broom::tidy)
  ) |> 
  select(.id, results) |> 
  unnest(results)

make into dataframe, fit a linear model, extract results

bootstrap_results |> 
  group_by(term) |> 
  summarize(
    mean = mean(estimate),

  • bootstrapping is good for if your sample is big enough, it will give you a sample that matches what you want (kind of like matching concept??)
  • can also be used to double check models produced by lm

revisit the airbnb dataset

data("nyc_airbnb")

nyc_airbnb = 
  nyc_airbnb |> 
  mutate(stars = review_scores_location / 2) |> 
  rename(
    borough = neighbourhood_group
    ) |> 
  filter(
    borough != "Staten Island"
  ) |> 
  drop_na(price, stars, room_type) |> 
  select(price, stars, room_type, borough)

what does this dataset look like again??

nyc_airbnb |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = stars, y = price, color = room_type)) +
  geom_point(alpha = .5)

try to do the bootstrap

airbnb_bootstrap_results = 
  nyc_airbnb |> 
  filter(borough == "Manhattan") |> 
  bootstrap(n = 1000) |> 
  mutate(
    df = map(strap, as_tibble), 
    fits = map(df, \(df) lm(price ~ stars + room_type, data = df)),
    results = map(fits, broom::tidy)
  ) |> 
  select(.id, results) |> 
  unnest(results)

Look at the distribution of the slope for stars.

airbnb_bootstrap_results |> 
  filter(term == "stars") |> 
  ggplot(aes(x = estimate)) +
  geom_density()
